column125: we wanted to buy a 3 series machine - the price of the machine is OK, the price of a click is OK but we have huge reservations about the service. No service program: (daily, monthly, annual inspections, unplanned service, monitoring of technical condition, modernizations and modifications, management of documentation based on mileage - spare parts and preventive, replacement of spare parts, reminders, training to improve staff qualifications on site) What Digiprint offers: 24h response, replacement of parts and sending a technician (level of training unknown). Such a system is unacceptable, in which 95% is done by the customer and digiprint, so-called RemoteSupport, sends buckets of parts, which after replacement, if there is still a problem, the order goes into the status - HP is working on it and we can't do anything about it. We are currently working on 5600 according to our own service program and annual certification of our machine for 100% compliance of work with the assumption (checking key parts, making adjustments, replacing consumables, rubber pads, etc.) For 7 years we had 1 visit to replace the computer under the warranty - the SERVICE PROGRAM practically eliminates unplanned failures and machine downs to just bad luck. The FLAT RATE rate of 3.5 k per month is completely unsuited to the current market and unacceptable - especially in a situation where competitive machines are entering the market with simpler machines, lower costs (both printing and service), and the Chinese are lurking around the corner with materials as well.

column125: What has always characterized Indigo has been the personal and warm relationship between customers, management, the service team, the sales team, and basically everyone. This has also been one of its greatest strengths, because you actually bought a machine from Indigo people and not from HP. Without maintaining this personal and close relationship, patience for malfunctions (which obviously happen), and for prices that are higher than the competition, and for price increases that have happened too many times recently, will decrease and harm customers' desire to renew with new Indigo equipment. Another problem is the problem of a shortage of operators, which causes a high cost of an operator to the printing house, which also affects the cost of labor, and hence a high cost to the customer, and hence, great difficulty in selling jobs produced on an Indigo machine.

column159:

The sustainability question again is something we have been on several calls with HP about recently.  HP is far behind in the US versus Europe and I feel like more can be done to remove waste from the Indigo process mostly through recycling.  We will continue to push this initiative as our customers are demanding a reduction in Scope 3 emissions.

We are far enough from our closest service tech that same day service is rarely an option, so when a technician provides support over the phone rather than coming here, it presents a problem.

In addition, techs do not seem to be prepared to stay overnight in the area when needed. This presents issues when they have a 3-4 hour drive here and back, then are only able to put in a partial day before they start worrying about betting home.

column116:
Our HP Indigo 7900 is a great fit for our needs at Stolze because of its versatility, high-quality output, and efficiency.

1. Exceptional Print Quality
HP Indigo delivers offset-quality digital printing, which is essential for producing premium packaging and direct mail pieces. It offers **sharp text, vibrant colors, and smooth gradients**, making it ideal for high-end print jobs.

2. Variable Data & Personalization
Indigo 7900 is great for variable data printing, allowing us to create personalized direct mail campaigns with unique names, addresses, and even images.
This is a big advantage in direct marketing and customized packaging.  

3. Cost-Effective for Short Runs
Unlike traditional offset printing, the Indigo is cost-effective for short runs without compromising on quality.

Overall, the HP Indigo enhances our capabilities at Stolze by combining quality, versatility, and efficiency, making it a key asset for Stolze Printing.

Si , HP esta muy  enfocada a sus equipos , pero no tanto al desarrollo de productos nuevos sobre los mismos .
Recuerdo aun el VIP DE 2019 en la planta de ISRAEL  , en donde había un corredor lleno de desarrollos de productos .

column125:
Yes, HP is very focused on its equipment, but not so much on developing new products on them.
I still remember the VIP 2019 at the ISRAEL plant, where there was a corridor full of product developments.
In essence, it is a race against technologies that destroy graphic products.
Yes, you also have developments that we will never be able to use: security passports, brand protection issues that our market does not pay for.
For all this, we live looking at what other products we could make at Indigo, it is in our DNA. A legacy that is 105 years old.

column116:
There are various opportunities to explore with this press. However, one key area for improvement is ensuring color consistency. Additionally, addressing customer issues promptly when escalated by a channel partner is crucial. The problem-solving process needs to be more efficient and responsive.

Despite escalating the matter to HP, no prompt action was taken. Moving forward, we would appreciate proactive solutions rather than simply being informed that a case has been escalated and that we need to wait. As customers, we expect a structured approach to problem-solving, with a focus on minimizing downtime and improving response times.

We hope HP and its partners will take these concerns into account and work towards a more effective support system.

column120: While we appreciate the efforts of the engineers who come on-site, the management of manpower and scheduling has been a challenging experience. In many cases, we have had to wait 23 days, sometimes even up to a week, for a response, resulting in certain issues remaining unresolved for 36 months. For instance, we faced a particular issue since September 2024, which was only resolved in February 2025. Additionally, maintenance reports were not sent via email as expected, and despite escalating the matter to HP, no prompt action was taken. As a printing company operating six days a week in Malaysia, the difference in working schedules with engineers, who operate on a five-day workweek, further delays issue resolutionoften requiring us to wait through the weekend. Moving forward, we would appreciate proactive solutions rather than just being informed that a case has been escalated and that we need to wait. As customers, we expect a structured approach to problem-solving, with a focus on minimizing downtime and improving response times. We hope HP and its partners can take these concerns into account and work towards a more effective support system.

column124:
Appreciate the support provided; however, there are unresolved issues that need to be addressed.

Regarding the supplies lifespan report, it has been arriving late, sometimes only after a month, and in some cases, after two months of not receiving any report (since December 2025, no report has been received). What is the next course of action for this supplies lifespan tracking? This is a critical concern as it directly impacts costs.

For the maintenance report, in compliance with ISO requirements, all reports must be archived. However, despite having a press that generates reports, we are unable to export them as expected (reports should be received via email). This issue remains unresolved.

We seek clarification and a concrete resolution plan to ensure smooth operations and compliance.

Regarding the supplies lifespan report, it has been arriving late, sometimes only after a month, and in some cases, after two months of not receiving any report (since December 2025, no report has been received). What is the next course of action for this supplies lifespan tracking? This is a critical concern as it directly impacts costs.

For the maintenance report, in compliance with ISO requirements, all reports must be archived. However, despite having a press that generates reports, we are unable to export them as expected (reports should be received via email). This issue remains unresolved.

We seek clarification and a concrete resolution plan to ensure smooth operations and compliance.

column129: There are issues with sales. I am satisfied with the service. See the next section for details.
column133:
Firstly, talk of delays in delivery of UTK and VP started even after the contract was signed.
The story changed several times, and we didn't receive any information unless we pressed for it.
Also, while the UTK has finally been delivered, the VP is still unclear.
There has been a request from Israel to remove the current 10,000, but it is unclear how long it will take to install the VP.
Including the fact that we have to keep it as a backup, the original business plan has fallen apart, and a huge opportunity loss has occurred.
The gap between the enthusiasm leading up to selling the 15K and what has happened since is too big.
column159:
First, the service staff.

- Uematsu-san
Your communication skills are outstanding, and I learn something from you every time.

You also respond to our requests (including slightly troublesome issues) in a detailed manner.

I was impressed by how happy you were every time a machine with problems was fixed, and I think you are a truly wonderful customer-oriented serviceman.

- Kanzaki-san
You came in the evening to deal with a Duplex problem, and I was impressed by how you continued to work on it until late at night without giving up.

It turned out that the hose, which was the most visible part, had come loose, but I am grateful for your logical thinking in isolating the cause one by one and arriving at that conclusion, and for your hard work without giving up. Thank you for working so late.

- Furukawa-san
The machine went down due to a relay failure at 10,000.
You also assigned us to deal with this sudden failure in the evening.

I am grateful that you continued to work on it without giving up despite the intense pressure I put on you.

The other day, I was unable to respond calmly to a situation where the delivery date was delayed, and I put unnecessary pressure on you.
Once again, I would like to express my deep gratitude. Please come again.

I just want to do a good job. Please don't misunderstand that.

-Takeuchi-san
I felt that he was a top-class engineer in terms of his skills, speed of thought, and logic.

Even during remote sessions, he was very attentive to our situation (remaining work, deadlines, etc.), and I am always grateful for his help.

-Saito-san
I was impressed by his response, which was backed by his experience, and his wealth of knowledge and speed of judgment are both excellent.

Sometimes he speaks a little fast on the phone and it's hard to hear, but I take that as a sign of his enthusiasm and consideration for us, and he is always grateful for our help.

Sales staff
-Oishi-san
He's doing a great job. When we were considering introducing 15K, we were leaning towards 99%R's products, but he completely turned it around. Even though he had the backing of the service, I think it was the sales effort.
I'm sorry about the delivery time for UTK and VP, but I fully understand that it's not Oishi's fault.

But that's why sales exist. If the product is excellent in all aspects of QCD and can achieve customer satisfaction without any effort, there's no need for sales.

Please understand that and continue to do your best.

-Chiba

I especially trust him because he is always calm and collected and never gives a zero answer to any of the things I ask him about. I feel relieved that he is backing up Oishi.

-Tonami

I don't see him often, but I can see that he is backing up the two people mentioned above. He is also trusted by all the Servo staff, so I can use Indigo with peace of mind.

Extra

-Yoyogi

Thank you for the delivery. It was fun to check the level together.

I could tell from the communication during the delivery that you have deep knowledge.

It's like saying that you can tell everything about a good martial artist by the way they wear their uniform.

Please come again.

Kunii-san
I was surprised that someone of Kunii's caliber would help with the delivery with a fork in hand.
You have extensive connections with external partner companies, and we are extremely grateful that the delivery went so smoothly.

column124:
I am disappointed and frustrated by HPs decision to unilaterally change the SmartStream user agreement from a CC license to a subscription-based model without any prior notification to existing users. This changeparticularly at a cost of $150 per month per seatis not only unexpected but also financially burdensome.
The fact that this transition was undoubtedly under consideration well before its implementation, yet we were never informed or given the opportunity to prepare for such a shift, is deeply concerning. This lack of transparency and failure to notify existing users in advance raises serious ethical and potential legal concerns. Companies operating in good faith do not impose major financial obligations on their customers without fair warning and consultation.
HPs decision will place an undue and unforeseen financial strain on our business.  Personally, I anticipate that this will generate significant backlash within the community. Furthermore, this type of unilateral modification to licensing agreements can easily lead to legal complexities and disputes, particularly when customers have relied on previous terms in good faith.
We strongly urge HP to reconsider this approach and provide an immediate resolutionwhether that be grandfathering in existing users under the previous terms, offering an alternative licensing model, or delaying implementation until a proper transition plan has been communicated and agreed upon by your user base.
I expect a prompt and detailed response addressing how HP intends to rectify this situation.

column116: The print quality of the HP Indigo is unmatched; however, the machines themselves can be unreliable. We also find that service cases are often marked as "closed" without any real resolution. Additionally, the lifespan score rebate/charge system is somewhat off-putting. column158:
We are actively exploring the purchase of a 200K within the next twelve months. However, receiving a lifespan charge on our existing 25K at the same time is discouraging. As we consider expanding with HP, it is frustrating to feel nickel-and-dimed over consumable usageespecially when inconsistent equipment performance is a contributing factor.

After raising our concerns, this charge has been paused, but the issue remains unresolved. One key reason our lifespan score has not met HPs targets is that the presss BCS has not been functioning properly for months. Despite multiple service requests, the case was prematurely closed without a real solutionsomething weve experienced far too often.

It is difficult to justify a further investment in HP when we are penalized for factors beyond our control, especially when those factors stem from equipment that has not performed to standard.
